unity run energy facilities with local control. His ideas on energy efficiency and saving electricity are truly brilliant, Yales is right there is no arguing against them, but I do not agree with his philosophy that we should ignore certain technology simply because it does not fit into the society he invisions. Lovins himself said that the soft path works best in a rural or dense urben society, one which does not truly resemble our own. In my opinion, and that is all that it is, we should look to solutions within the current framework, there is no need to restructure our society to improve our environmental stance. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1161<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/16/03 6:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=182.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: most people aren't fit for human consumption!</span><hr size=1> Many of the environmentalists that I've read like Peter Hoffman and Jeremy Rifkin express similiar ideas about decentralizing power production.  This in itself wouldn't really bother me much if it wasn't for the fact that most of these advocates are against even doing research into nuclear energy sources.  Even if we arbitrarily condemn most of society to existing on low amounts of wattage, it would still be nice to have advanced and powerful sources of energy for applications like spaceflight and for the general advancement of science. We'll never reach the stars if our power comes from the blade of a windmill or current chemicals (even solar sails will need terrawatts of laser power if they're meant to reach relativistic velocities.)  My general impression of most 'renewable energy' advocates is that they don't really support the advancement of science and technology when it goes beyond their pet theories on how energy should be generated.  They need to be more flexible and realize that there is a place for nuclear energy even if it isn't on Earth but most of them identify with the Gagnon mob when it comes to those issues. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :puke --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_klein_1/puke.gif ALT=":puke"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=x@nuclearspace>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 214<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/16/03 12:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=182.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: most people aren't fit for human consumption!</span><hr size=1> Lovins is a Luddite.  One thing Luddites want is to stop progress.  One good way to bring progress to a grinding halt is to reduce our ability to produce large amounts of energy in a small area.  It's what's needed for space travel, terraforming, massive earth-moving projects (building canals, underground facilities, etc.), and industrialization and manufacturing.  Also, he said that we needed to decentralize our power productions to keep humanity from doing mischief and harm to the earth.  That is a basic tenant of the extreme environmental movement.  His plan will give us humanity just enough to get by on.  There will be no progress; just stagnation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 150<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/20/03 9:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=182.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: most people aren't fit for human consumption!</span><hr size=1> untill now, the luddite's goal never quite hit home. They wish to snuff out the flame of creativity and exploring, the things that will lead humanity into a future thats bright. How dare they. If they prevail, will we even still be human? May they fail, the other possibility is to dark for even me to contemplate. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mylenejenius@nuclearspace>MyleneJenius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/21/03 4:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=182.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.csclub.uwaterloo.ca/u/yhchan/gallery/mylene/thumbnail/Mac704.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: most p